[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A **regular expression** (shortened as **regex** or **regexp**), sometimes referred to as a **rational expression**, is a sequence of characters that specifies a match pattern in text.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Usually such patterns are used by string-searching algorithms for "find" or "find and replace" operations on strings, or for input validation.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expression techniques are developed in theoretical computer science and formal language theory.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The concept of regular expressions began in the 1950s, when the American mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene formalized the concept of a regular language.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] They came into common use with Unix text-processing utilities.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Different syntaxes for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the POSIX standard and another, widely used, being the Perl syntax.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are used in search engines, in search and replace dialogs of word processors and text editors, in text processing utilities such as sed and AWK, and in lexical analysis.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions are supported in many programming languages.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Library implementations are often called an "engine", and many of these are available for reuse.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions originated in 1951, when mathematician Stephen Cole Kleene described regular languages using his mathematical notation called *regular events*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] These arose in theoretical computer science, in the subfields of automata theory (models of computation) and the description and classification of formal languages, motivated by Kleene's attempt to describe early artificial neural networks.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions entered popular use from 1968 in two uses: pattern matching in a text editor and lexical analysis in a compiler.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Among the first appearances of regular expressions in program form was when Ken Thompson built Kleene's notation into the editor QED as a means to match patterns in text files.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by just-in-time compilation (JIT) to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System, an important early example of JIT compilation.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Around the same time that Thompson developed QED, a group of researchers including Douglas T.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Ross implemented a tool based on regular expressions that is used for lexical analysis in compiler design.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Many variations of these original forms of regular expressions were used in Unix programs at Bell Labs in the 1970s, including lex, sed, AWK, and expr, and in other programs such as vi, and Emacs (which has its own, incompatible syntax and behavior).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regexes were subsequently adopted by a wide range of programs, with these early forms standardized in the POSIX.2 standard in 1992.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In the 1980s, the more complicated regexes arose in Perl, which originally derived from a regex library written by Henry Spencer (1986), who later wrote an implementation for Tcl called *Advanced Regular Expressions*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The Tcl library is a hybrid NFA/DFA implementation with improved performance characteristics.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Software projects that have adopted Spencer's Tcl regular expression implementation include PostgreSQL.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Perl later expanded on Spencer's original library to add many new features.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Part of the effort in the design of Raku (formerly named Perl 6) is to improve Perl's regex integration, and to increase their scope and capabilities to allow the definition of parsing expression grammars.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The result is a mini-language called Raku rules, which are used to define Raku grammar as well as provide a tool to programmers in the language.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] These rules maintain existing features of Perl 5.x regexes, but also allow BNF-style definition of a recursive descent parser via sub-rules.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The use of regexes in structured information standards for document and database modeling started in the 1960s and expanded in the 1980s when industry standards like ISO SGML (precursored by ANSI "GCA 101-1983") consolidated.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The kernel of the structure specification language standards consists of regexes.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Its use is evident in the DTD element group syntax.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Prior to the use of regular expressions, many search languages allowed simple wildcards, for example "*" to match any sequence of characters, and "?" to match a single character.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Relics of this can be found today in the glob syntax for filenames, and in the SQL `LIKE` operator.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Starting in 1997, Philip Hazel developed PCRE (Perl Compatible Regular Expressions), which attempts to closely mimic Perl's regex functionality and is used by many modern tools including PHP and Apache HTTP Server.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Today, regexes are widely supported in programming languages, text processing programs (particularly lexers), advanced text editors, and some other programs.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regex support is part of the standard library of many programming languages, including Java and Python, and is built into the syntax of others, including Perl and ECMAScript.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The phrase *regular expressions*, or *regexes*, is often used to mean the specific, standard textual syntax for representing patterns for matching text, as distinct from the mathematical notation described below.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Each character in a regular expression (that is, each character in the string describing its pattern) is either a metacharacter, having a special meaning, or a regular character that has a literal meaning.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, in the regex `b.`, 'b' is a literal character that matches just 'b', while '.' is a metacharacter that matches every character except a newline.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Therefore, this regex matches, for example, 'b%', or 'bx', or 'b5'.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Together, metacharacters and literal characters can be used to identify text of a given pattern or process a number of instances of it.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Pattern matches may vary from a precise equality to a very general similarity, as controlled by the metacharacters.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, `.` is a very general pattern, `[a-z]` (match all lowercase letters from 'a' to 'z') is less general and `b` is a precise pattern (matches just 'b').
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The metacharacter syntax is designed specifically to represent prescribed targets in a concise and flexible way to direct the automation of text processing of a variety of input data, in a form easy to type using a standard ASCII keyboard.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A very simple case of a regular expression in this syntax is to locate a word spelled two different ways in a text editor; for example, the regular expression `seriali[sz]e` matches both "serialise" and "serialize".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Wildcard characters also achieve this, but are more limited in what they can pattern, as they have fewer metacharacters and a simple language-base.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The usual context of wildcard characters is in globbing similar names in a list of files, whereas regexes are usually employed in applications that pattern-match text strings in general.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, the regex `^[ \t]+|[ \t]+$` matches excess whitespace at the beginning or end of a line.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A **regex processor** translates a regular expression in the above syntax into an internal representation that can be executed and matched against a string representing the text being searched in.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] One possible approach is the Thompson's construction algorithm to construct a nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA), which is then made deterministic and the resulting deterministic finite automaton (DFA) is run on the target text string to recognize substrings that match the regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The picture shows the NFA scheme `*N*(*s**)` obtained from the regular expression `*s**`, where *s* denotes a simpler regular expression in turn, which has already been recursively translated to the NFA *N*(*s*).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A regular expression, often called a *pattern*, specifies a set of strings required for a particular purpose.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A simple way to specify a finite set of strings is to list its elements or members.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, there are often more concise ways: for example, the set containing the three strings "Handel", "Händel", and "Haendel" can be specified by the pattern `H(ä|ae?)ndel`; we say that this pattern *matches* each of the three strings.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, there can be many ways to write a regular expression for the same set of strings: for example, `(Hän|Han|Haen)del` also specifies the same set of three strings in this example.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Most formalisms provide the following operations to construct regular expressions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] are equivalent patterns which both describe the set of "gray" or "grey".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] , character, or group) specifies how many times the preceding element is allowed to repeat.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then any character and then "b".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] matches any string that contains an "a", and then the character "b" at some later point.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] These constructions can be combined to form arbitrarily complex expressions, much like one can construct arithmetical expressions from numbers and the operations +, −, ×, and ÷.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The precise syntax for regular expressions varies among tools and with context; more detail is given in § Syntax.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions describe regular languages in formal language theory.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] They have the same expressive power as regular grammars.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] But the language of regular expressions itself, is context-free language.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions consist of constants, which denote sets of strings, and operator symbols, which denote operations over these sets.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The following definition is standard, and found as such in most textbooks on formal language theory.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] To avoid parentheses, it is assumed that the Kleene star has the highest priority followed by concatenation, then alternation.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] If there is no ambiguity, then parentheses may be omitted.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, `(ab)c` can be written as `abc`, and `a|(b(c*))` can be written as `a|bc*`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Many textbooks use the symbols ∪, +, or ∨ for alternation instead of the vertical bar.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The derivative of a regular expression can be defined using the Brzozowski derivative.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The formal definition of regular expressions is minimal on purpose, and avoids defining `?` and `+`—these can be expressed as follows: `a+`=`aa*`, and `a?`=`(a|ε)`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Sometimes the complement operator is added, to give a *generalized regular expression*; here *Rc* matches all strings over Σ* that do not match *R*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In principle, the complement operator is redundant, because it does not grant any more expressive power.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, it can make a regular expression much more concise—eliminating a single complement operator can cause a double exponential blow-up of its length.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Regular expressions in this sense can express the regular languages, exactly the class of languages accepted by deterministic finite automata.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] There is, however, a significant difference in compactness.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Some classes of regular languages can only be described by deterministic finite automata whose size grows exponentially in the size of the shortest equivalent regular expressions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The standard example here is the languages *Lk* consisting of all strings over the alphabet {*a*,*b*} whose *k*th-from-last letter equals *a*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] On the one hand, a regular expression describing *L*4 is given by $(a\mid b)^{*}a(a\mid b)(a\mid b)(a\mid b)$ .
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] On the other hand, it is known that every deterministic finite automaton accepting the language *Lk* must have at least 2*k* states.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Luckily, there is a simple mapping from regular expressions to the more general nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs) that does not lead to such a blowup in size; for this reason NFAs are often used as alternative representations of regular languages.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] NFAs are a simple variation of the type-3 grammars of the Chomsky hierarchy.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In the opposite direction, there are many languages easily described by a DFA that are not easily described by a regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For instance, determining the validity of a given ISBN requires computing the remainder of an integer modulo 11, and can be easily implemented with an 11-state DFA.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, converting it to a regular expression results in a 2.14-megabyte file.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Given a regular expression, Thompson's construction algorithm computes an equivalent nondeterministic finite automaton.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A conversion in the opposite direction is achieved by Kleene's algorithm.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Finally, many real-world "regular expression" engines implement features that cannot be described by the regular expressions in the sense of formal language theory; rather, they implement *regexes*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] As seen in many of the examples above, there is more than one way to construct a regular expression to achieve the same results.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] It is possible to write an algorithm that, for two given regular expressions, decides whether the described languages are equal; the algorithm reduces each expression to a minimal deterministic finite state machine, and determines whether they are isomorphic (equivalent).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] More generally, an equation *E*=*F* between regular-expression terms with variables holds if, and only if, its instantiation with different variables replaced by different symbol constants holds.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Every regular expression can be written solely in terms of the Kleene star and set unions over finite words.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This is a surprisingly difficult problem.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] As simple as the regular expressions are, there is no method to systematically rewrite them to some normal form.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The lack of axiom in the past led to the star height problem.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In 1991, Dexter Kozen axiomatized regular expressions as a Kleene algebra, using equational and Horn clause axioms.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Already in 1964, Redko had proved that no finite set of purely equational axioms can characterize the algebra of regular languages.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A regex *pattern* matches a target *string*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The pattern is composed of a sequence of *atoms*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] An atom is a single point within the regex pattern which it tries to match to the target string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The simplest atom is a literal, but grouping parts of the pattern to match an atom will require using `( )` as metacharacters.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A match is made, not when all the atoms of the string are matched, but rather when all the pattern atoms in the regex have matched.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The idea is to make a small pattern of characters stand for a large number of possible strings, rather than compiling a large list of all the literal possibilities.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Depending on the regex processor there are about fourteen metacharacters, characters that may or may not have their literal character meaning, depending on context, or whether they are "escaped", i.e. preceded by an escape sequence, in this case, the backslash `\`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The usual characters that become metacharacters when escaped are `dswDSW` and `N`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] When entering a regex in a programming language, they may be represented as a usual string literal, hence usually quoted; this is common in C, Java, and Python for instance, where the regex `re` is entered as `"re"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, they are often written with slashes as delimiters, as in `/re/` for the regex `re`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A similar convention is used in sed, where search and replace is given by `s/re/replacement/` and patterns can be joined with a comma to specify a range of lines as in `/re1/,/re2/`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This notation is particularly well known due to its use in Perl, where it forms part of the syntax distinct from normal string literals.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In some cases, such as sed and Perl, alternative delimiters can be used to avoid collision with contents, and to avoid having to escape occurrences of the delimiter character in the contents.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, in sed the command `s,/,X,` will replace a `/` with an `X`, using commas as delimiters.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The IEEE POSIX standard has three sets of compliance: **BRE** (Basic Regular Expressions), **ERE** (Extended Regular Expressions), and **SRE** (Simple Regular Expressions).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] SRE is deprecated, in favor of BRE, as both provide backward compatibility.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The subsection below covering the *character classes* applies to both BRE and ERE.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] ERE adds `?`, `+`, and `|`, and it removes the need to escape the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }`, which are *required* in BRE.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Furthermore, as long as the POSIX standard syntax for regexes is adhered to, there can be, and often is, additional syntax to serve specific (yet POSIX compliant) applications.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Although POSIX.2 leaves some implementation specifics undefined, BRE and ERE provide a "standard" which has since been adopted as the default syntax of many tools, where the choice of BRE or ERE modes is usually a supported option.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, GNU `grep` has the following options: "`grep -E`" for ERE, and "`grep -G`" for BRE (the default), and "`grep -P`" for Perl regexes.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Perl regexes have become a de facto standard, having a rich and powerful set of atomic expressions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Perl has no "basic" or "extended" levels.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] As in POSIX EREs, `( )` and `{ }` are treated as metacharacters unless escaped; other metacharacters are known to be literal or symbolic based on context alone.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Additional functionality includes lazy matching, backreferences, named capture groups, and recursive patterns.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In the POSIX standard, Basic Regular Syntax (**BRE**) requires that the metacharacters `( )` and `{ }` be designated `\(\)` and `\{\}`, whereas Extended Regular Syntax (**ERE**) does not.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] According to Russ Cox, the POSIX specification requires ambiguous subexpressions to be handled in a way different from Perl's.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The committee replaced Perl's rules with one that is simple to explain, but the new "simple" rules are actually more complex to implement: they were incompatible with pre-existing tooling and made it essentially impossible to define a "lazy match" (see below) extension.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] As a result, very few programs actually implement the POSIX subexpression rules (even when they implement other parts of the POSIX syntax).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The meaning of metacharacters escaped with a backslash is reversed for some characters in the POSIX Extended Regular Expression (**ERE**) syntax.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] With this syntax, a backslash causes the metacharacter to be treated as a literal character.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] POSIX Extended Regular Expressions can often be used with modern Unix utilities by including the command line flag *-E*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The character class is the most basic regex concept after a literal match.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] It makes one small sequence of characters match a larger set of characters.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[A-Z]` could stand for any uppercase letter in the English alphabet, and `\d` could mean any digit.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Character classes apply to both POSIX levels.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] When specifying a range of characters, such as `[a-Z]` (i.e. lowercase *`a`* to uppercase *`Z`*), the computer's locale settings determine the contents by the numeric ordering of the character encoding.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] They could store digits in that sequence, or the ordering could be *abc...zABC...Z*, or *aAbBcC...zZ*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] So the POSIX standard defines a character class, which will be known by the regex processor installed.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, `[[:upper:]ab]` matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is `[:word:]`, which is usually defined as `[:alnum:]` plus underscore.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Note that what the POSIX regex standards call *character classes* are commonly referred to as *POSIX character classes* in other regex flavors which support them.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] With most other regex flavors, the term *character class* is used to describe what POSIX calls *bracket expressions*.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to Perl's—for example, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Python, Ruby, Qt, Microsoft's .NET Framework, and XML Schema.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Some languages and tools such as Boost and PHP support multiple regex flavors.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In Python and some other implementations (e.g.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Java), the three common quantifiers (`*`, `+`, and `?`) are greedy by default because they match as many characters as possible.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made *lazy* or *minimal* or *reluctant*, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: `".+?"` matches only `"Ganymede,"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] matches the entire line, the regex `".*+"` does *not match at all*, because `.*+` consumes the entire input, including the final `"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] `"[^"]*+"`, which matches `"Ganymede,"` when applied to the same string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, while ^(wi|w)i$ matches both wi and wii, ^(?>wi|w)i$ only matches wii because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and so cannot try setting the group to "w" after matching "wi".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] IETF RFC 9485 describes "I-Regexp: An Interoperable Regular Expression Format".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] It specifies a limited subset of regular-expression idioms designed to be interoperable, i.e. produce the same effect, in a large number of regular-expression libraries.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] I-Regexp is also limited to matching, i.e. providing a true or false match between a regular expression and a given piece of text.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Thus, it lacks advanced features such as capture groups, lookahead, and backreferences.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the regular languages.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (*backreferences*).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called *squares* in formal language theory.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The pattern for these strings is `(.+)\1`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The language of squares is not regular, nor is it context-free, due to the pumping lemma.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, pattern matching with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still context sensitive.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is NP-complete, and the execution time for known algorithms grows exponentially by the number of backreference groups used.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term *regular expression* for their patterns.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in formal language theory and pattern matching.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For this reason, some people have taken to using the term *regex*, *regexp*, or simply *pattern* to describe the latter.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] These include the ubiquitous `^` and `$`, used since at least 1970, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround that appeared in 1994.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Lookarounds define the surrounding of a match and do not spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The look-ahead assertions `(?=...)` and `(?!...)` have been attested since at least 1994, starting with Perl 5.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The lookbehind assertions `(?<=...)` and `(?<!...)` are attested since 1997 in a commit by Ilya Zakharevich to Perl 5.005.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] There are at least three different algorithms that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) to be transformed into a deterministic finite automaton (DFA).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size *m* has the time and memory cost of *O*(2*m*), but it can be run on a string of size *n* in time *O*(*n*).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to *O*(*mn*).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox's code.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by backtracking.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like `(a|aa)*b` that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] This behavior can cause a security problem called Regular expression Denial of Service (ReDoS).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Wu agrep, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] NR-grep's BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})$ ⁠ time and ⁠ ${\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})$ ⁠ space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use ASCII characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other character sets.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for Unicode.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p01] Most general-purpose programming languages support regex capabilities, either natively or via libraries.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally string processing, where the data need not be textual.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Common applications include data validation, data scraping (especially web scraping), data wrangling, simple parsing, the production of syntax highlighting systems, and many other tasks.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Some high-end desktop publishing software has the ability to use regexes to automatically apply text styling, saving the person doing the layout from laboriously doing this by hand for anything that can be matched by a regex.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] For example, by defining a character style that makes text into small caps and then using the regex `[A-Z]{4,}` to apply that style, any word of four or more consecutive capital letters will be automatically rendered as small caps instead.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] While regexes would be useful on Internet search engines, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Notable exceptions include Google Code Search and Exalead.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, programming language, or library in use.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between versions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] This section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] The following conventions are used in the examples.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Standard POSIX regular expressions are different.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the Perl programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, `\( \)` vs.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] This is known as the induction of regular languages and is part of the general problem of grammar induction in computational learning theory.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings *not* in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see language identification in the limit), but many can.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expression-p02] For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1⋅0* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Regular expressions are patterns used to match character combinations in strings.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] In JavaScript, regular expressions are also objects.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] These patterns are used with the `exec()` and `test()` methods of `RegExp`, and with the `match()`, `matchAll()`, `replace()`, `replaceAll()`, `search()`, and `split()` methods of `String`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] This chapter describes JavaScript regular expressions.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] It provides a brief overview of each syntax element.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For a detailed explanation of each one's semantics, read the regular expressions reference.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] A regular expression pattern is composed of simple characters, such as `/abc/`, or a combination of simple and special characters, such as `/ab*c/` or `/Chapter (\d+)\.\d*/`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The last example includes parentheses, which are used as a memory device.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The match made with this part of the pattern is remembered for later use, as described in Using groups.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Simple patterns are constructed of characters for which you want to find a direct match.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For example, the pattern `/abc/` matches character combinations in strings only when the exact sequence `"abc"` occurs (all characters together and in that order).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Such a match would succeed in the strings `"Hi, do you know your abc's?"` and `"The latest airplane designs evolved from slabcraft."`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] In both cases the match is with the substring `"abc"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] There is no match in the string `"Grab crab"` because while it contains the substring `"ab c"`, it does not contain the exact substring `"abc"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] When the search for a match requires something more than a direct match, such as finding one or more b's, or finding white space, you can include special characters in the pattern.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For example, to match *a single `"a"` followed by zero or more `"b"`s followed by `"c"`*, you'd use the pattern `/ab*c/`: the `*` after `"b"` means "0 or more occurrences of the preceding item." In the string `"cbbabbbbcdebc"`, this pattern will match the substring `"abbbbc"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The following pages provide lists of the different special characters that fit into each category, along with descriptions and examples.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Assertions include boundaries, which indicate the beginnings and endings of lines and words, and other patterns indicating in some way that a match is possible (including look-ahead, look-behind, and conditional expressions).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Distinguish different types of characters.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For example, distinguishing between letters and digits.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Groups group multiple patterns as a whole, and capturing groups provide extra submatch information when using a regular expression pattern to match against a string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Backreferences refer to a previously captured group in the same regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Indicate numbers of characters or expressions to match.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If you need to use any of the special characters literally (actually searching for a `"*"`, for instance), you should escape it by putting a backslash in front of it.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For instance, to search for `"a"` followed by `"*"` followed by `"b"`, you'd use `/a\*b/` — the backslash "escapes" the `"*"`, making it literal instead of special.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Similarly, if you're writing a regular expression literal and need to match a slash ("/"), you need to escape that (otherwise, it terminates the pattern).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For instance, to search for the string "/example/" followed by one or more alphabetic characters, you'd use `/\/example\/[a-z]+/i`—the backslashes before each slash make them literal.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] To match a literal backslash, you need to escape the backslash.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For instance, to match the string "C:\" where "C" can be any letter, you'd use `/[A-Z]:\\/` — the first backslash escapes the one after it, so the expression searches for a single literal backslash.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If using the `RegExp` constructor with a string literal, remember that the backslash is an escape in string literals, so to use it in the regular expression, you need to escape it at the string literal level.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] `/a\*b/` and `new RegExp("a\\*b")` create the same expression, which searches for "a" followed by a literal "*" followed by "b".
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The `RegExp.escape()` function returns a new string where all special characters in regex syntax are escaped.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] This allows you to do `new RegExp(RegExp.escape("a*b"))` to create a regular expression that matches only the string `"a*b"`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Parentheses around any part of the regular expression pattern causes that part of the matched substring to be remembered.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Once remembered, the substring can be recalled for other use.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] See Groups and backreferences for more details.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Regular expressions are used with the `RegExp` methods `test()` and `exec()` and with the `String` methods `match()`, `matchAll()`, `replace()`, `replaceAll()`, `search()`, and `split()`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] When you want to know whether a pattern is found in a string, use the `test()` or `search()` methods; for more information (but slower execution) use the `exec()` or `match()` methods.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If you use `exec()` or `match()` and if the match succeeds, these methods return an array and update properties of the associated regular expression object and also of the predefined regular expression object, `RegExp`.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If the match fails, the `exec()` method returns `null` (which coerces to `false`).
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] In the following example, the script uses the `exec()` method to find a match in a string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] With these scripts, the match succeeds and returns the array and updates the properties shown in the following table.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] As shown in the second form of this example, you can use a regular expression created with an object initializer without assigning it to a variable.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If you do, however, every occurrence is a new regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For this reason, if you use this form without assigning it to a variable, you cannot subsequently access the properties of that regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The occurrences of `/d(b+)d/g` in the two statements are different regular expression objects and hence have different values for their `lastIndex` property.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If you need to access the properties of a regular expression created with an object initializer, you should first assign it to a variable.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Regular expressions have optional flags that allow for functionality like global searching and case-insensitive searching.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] These flags can be used separately or together in any order, and are included as part of the regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Note that the flags are an integral part of a regular expression.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] For example, `re = /\w+\s/g` creates a regular expression that looks for one or more characters followed by a space, and it looks for this combination throughout the string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The `m` flag is used to specify that a multiline input string should be treated as multiple lines.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If the `m` flag is used, `^` and `$` match at the start or end of any line within the input string instead of the start or end of the entire string.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The `i`, `m`, and `s` flags can be enabled or disabled for specific parts of a regex using the modifier syntax.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] `RegExp.prototype.exec()` method with the `g` flag returns each match and its position iteratively.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] In contrast, `String.prototype.match()` method returns all matches at once, but without their position.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] The `u` flag is used to create "unicode" regular expressions; that is, regular expressions which support matching against unicode text.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] An important feature that's enabled in unicode mode is Unicode property escapes.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] Unicode regular expressions have different execution behavior as well.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] `RegExp.prototype.unicode` contains more explanation about this.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] In the following example, the user is expected to enter a phone number.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] When the user presses the "Check" button, the script checks the validity of the number.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If the number is valid (matches the character sequence specified by the regular expression), the script shows a message thanking the user and confirming the number.
[src:validator-strings/regular-expressions] If the number is invalid, the script informs the user that the phone number is not valid.
